      "text": "A 68-year-old woman with a history of chronic constipation and three prior pregnancies presents to the emergency department with a rectal mass. She notes worsening fecal incontinence over the last 6 months. On examination in left lateral position, a 4-cm pink mass with concentric mucosal folds protrudes from the anus. A deep sulcus is palpable between the mass and the anal canal walls. Which factor would most significantly determine the urgency of surgical referral?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Underlying chronic constipation"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Length of the prolapsed segment"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Presence of fecal incontinence"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "text": "Patient age and comorbidities"
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "text": "Ability to manually reduce the prolapse"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 5,
      "solution": "<div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>A) INCORRECT:</h4>Chronic <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=CM0qIg&anker=Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-learningcard-id=\"CM0qIg\" data-anker=\"Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-sememe-id=\"9DYNgr\">constipation</a> is a <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=ps0LDh&anker=Zbc0d0ff153bc5c7a27589815d0c842fd\" data-learningcard-id=\"ps0LDh\" data-anker=\"Zbc0d0ff153bc5c7a27589815d0c842fd\" data-section-id=\"FfWgLk0\" data-sememe-id=\"b31HSg0\">risk factor</a> for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=W30Phf&anker=Z5558e5113802e39d648202d1a455a052\" data-learningcard-id=\"W30Phf\" data-anker=\"Z5558e5113802e39d648202d1a455a052\" data-sememe-id=\"VO0GrT\">rectal prolapse</a> and influences surgical planning, and treatment of underlying <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=CM0qIg&anker=Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-learningcard-id=\"CM0qIg\" data-anker=\"Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-sememe-id=\"9DYNgr\">constipation</a> is important for preventing recurrence. Chronic <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=CM0qIg&anker=Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-learningcard-id=\"CM0qIg\" data-anker=\"Z65fd66f9cecf14d85a69e656c3a69417\" data-sememe-id=\"9DYNgr\">constipation</a> does not determine the urgency of referral.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>B) INCORRECT:</h4>While <span data-sememe-id=\"E5W8NN0\">full-thickness prolapse</span> requires surgical treatment, the length alone does not determine the urgency of surgical intervention. Both shorter and longer prolapses are generally managed electively unless there are complications that are indications for urgent treatment.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>C) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Vs0GFh&anker=Z62ff0b685d439994bb91355e521425cb\" data-learningcard-id=\"Vs0GFh\" data-anker=\"Z62ff0b685d439994bb91355e521425cb\" data-sememe-id=\"INWYcN0\">Fecal incontinence</a> is a common symptom of <span data-sememe-id=\"E5W8NN0\">full-thickness prolapse</span> due to anal sphincter stretching and is not an indication for urgent surgical intervention. <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Vs0GFh&anker=Z62ff0b685d439994bb91355e521425cb\" data-learningcard-id=\"Vs0GFh\" data-anker=\"Z62ff0b685d439994bb91355e521425cb\" data-sememe-id=\"INWYcN0\">Fecal incontinence</a> influences the surgical approach but not the timing.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>D) INCORRECT:</h4>Patient age and comorbidities influence the choice of surgical approach (abdominal vs. perineal procedures) but do not determine the urgency of referral.</div><div><h4 style='color: #34d399; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>E) CORRECT:</h4>Correct -- The ability to manually reduce the prolapse is the most critical factor determining urgency. Reducible prolapse can be managed with elective surgical referral, while incarcerated prolapse that cannot be reduced requires emergency surgical intervention, as it can lead to <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=VP0GdT&anker=Zbc05e544d46e794a60ac9ce9ec6883af\" data-learningcard-id=\"VP0GdT\" data-anker=\"Zbc05e544d46e794a60ac9ce9ec6883af\" data-section-id=\"k9cmne0\" data-sememe-id=\"WQ0PEf\">ischemia</a> and <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=VP0GdT&anker=Z28b2cd3d009fe208ee54280c99b41b38\" data-learningcard-id=\"VP0GdT\" data-anker=\"Z28b2cd3d009fe208ee54280c99b41b38\" data-section-id=\"R9clMe0\" data-sememe-id=\"O8aI5m\">necrosis</a>.</div>",
